<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-06-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-06-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="284" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d284">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 2540/8.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Fox</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-06-18"><hi rend="italic">June 18,
                                1907</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Fox informs Mr. Root, referring to previous correspondence<note n="a" xml:id="d284fna">Not printed.</note> eight, twelve, and also
                            fifteen, that the railway crisis is reached, and that revolution is
                            imminent owing to the railway problem. He also states that the American
                            investments are reported as being in danger, the people insisting on
                            confiscation. He further states that the railway company urges
                            arbitration of her contract. He asks for instructions.)</p>
                    </div>
